    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "The tracker idea makes sense, but I'm worried about the overhead of storing every single allocation size in a vector like that, especially on this hardware. \n\nIs there a way to do this more lightweight? Like, if the leak is really stealthy and just slowly eating away at the heap, how do I catch it without it looking like a massive spike? It feels like something is just hiding in the background and I can't see it.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The tracker idea does come with some overhead, especially if you're dealing with a large number of allocations. In that case, you might want to consider using a more lightweight approach.\n\nOne technique you could use is to keep track of the allocation history in a way that's more sparse, but still allows you to detect the leak. For example, you could use a simple bit vector to keep track of which allocations have been freed. This way, you can quickly check if an allocation has been freed without having to store the entire allocation history.\n\nAnother approach is to use a technique called \"leak detection via garbage collection\". The idea is to periodically run a garbage collection algorithm that goes through the heap and identifies any objects that are still reachable but have not been freed. If the garbage collection algorithm identifies a large number of objects that are still reachable, it could indicate a memory leak.\n\nHowever, these techniques might not be as effective as using a dedicated memory tracker, and they might require more complex code.\n\nYou could also try to use a simple heuristic, like the \" allocation frequency\" heuristic. This involves tracking the frequency of allocations in a given time window, and if the frequency is higher than a certain threshold, it could indicate a memory leak.\n\nIn",
